AMS Subject classification : 60J10
Key words and phrases: mixing time, MCMC, Gibbs sampler, topic model, Potts model
Short title: Rapid mixing and efficient simulated annealing

1 Introduction

Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) is a powerful tool for sampling from a given probability distribution on a very large state space, where direct sampling is difficult, in part because of the size of the state space and in part because of normalizing constants that are difficult to compute.

In machine learning in particular, MCMC algorithms are very common for sampling from posterior distributions of Bayesian probabilistic models. The posterior distribution given observed data turns out to be difficult to sample from for the reasons just mentioned. One then designs an (irreducible aperiodic) Markov chain whose stationary distribution is precisely the targeted posterior. This is usually fairly easy since the posterior is usually easy to compute up to the normalizing constant (the denominator in Bayes formula). A particularly popular choice is to use Metropolis-Hastings sampling (of which Gibbs sampling is a special case).

An all too common problem with these MCMC algorithms is that the target distribution contains several modes such that it is extremely hard for the MCMC to move between the modes. This may for example result in that one can get stuck for a virtually infinite time in a relatively small mode containing a negligible probability mass in the target distribution.

Our driving force will be a class of probability distributions on the d ùëë d italic_d -dimensional box B n d = { 0 , 1 / n , 2 / n , ‚Ä¶ , 1 } d superscript subscript ùêµ ùëõ ùëë superscript 0 1 ùëõ 2 ùëõ ‚Ä¶ 1 ùëë B_{n}^{d}=\{0,1/n,2/n,\ldots,1\}^{d} italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = { 0 , 1 / italic_n , 2 / italic_n , ‚Ä¶ , 1 } start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT that exhibit this problem and show that a very fast and very simple simulated annealing scheme yet provides convergence to the true distribution within the order of n 2 superscript ùëõ 2 n^{2} italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT steps. Furthermore, combining simulated annealing with a varying step size, this can even be taken down to order n log ‚Å° n ùëõ ùëõ n\log n italic_n roman_log italic_n . This class comprises an abundance of interesting examples, of which we will include the mean field Ising model with a nonzero external field, collapsed Gibbs sampling for Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA) and a model of nuclear physics; calibration data corresponding to the 3S1 phase shifts from an analysis of neutron-proton scattering cross sections [ 17 ] . In all of these cases, we have run a series of experiments, of which the LDA example are large scale whereas the others are on a smaller scale.

Let g : [ 0 , 1 ] d ‚Üí ( 0 , ‚àû ] : ùëî ‚Üí superscript 0 1 ùëë 0 g:[0,1]^{d}\rightarrow(0,\infty] italic_g : [ 0 , 1 ] start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Üí ( 0 , ‚àû ] be a bounded function. We want to sample from the probability distribution œÄ ùúã \pi italic_œÄ on B d subscript ùêµ ùëë B_{d} italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , given by

œÄ ( s ) = g ( s ) ‚àë u ‚àà B n d g ( u ) . ùúã ùë† ùëî ùë† subscript ùë¢ superscript subscript ùêµ ùëõ ùëë ùëî ùë¢ \pi(s)=\frac{g(s)}{\sum_{u\in B_{n}^{d}}g(u)}. italic_œÄ ( italic_s ) = divide start_ARG italic_g ( italic_s ) end_ARG start_ARG ‚àë start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_u ‚àà italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_g ( italic_u ) end_ARG .

Consider the following natural Metropolis hastings algorithm; standing in vertex u ùë¢ u italic_u , a vertex v ùë£ v italic_v among the 2 d 2 ùëë 2d 2 italic_d neighbors of u ùë¢ u italic_u is chosen uniformly at random and a move to v ùë£ v italic_v is proposed and then accepted with probability ( 1 / 2 ) g ( v ) / ( g ( u ) + g ( v ) ) 1 2 ùëî ùë£ ùëî ùë¢ ùëî ùë£ (1/2)g(v)/(g(u)+g(v)) ( 1 / 2 ) italic_g ( italic_v ) / ( italic_g ( italic_u ) + italic_g ( italic_v ) ) . If u ùë¢ u italic_u is on the boundary of the box, the algorithm still proposes moves in directions that lead out of the box, but such a move is of course not accepted; this feature can be achieved by for each boundary vertex u ùë¢ u italic_u adding one loop ( u , u ) ùë¢ ùë¢ (u,u) ( italic_u , italic_u ) for each direction leading out of the box and thereby making B n d superscript subscript ùêµ ùëõ ùëë B_{n}^{d} italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT regular (i.e.¬†all vertices have the same degree). We will refer to this MCMC algorithm as the weighted random walk on B n d superscript subscript ùêµ ùëõ ùëë B_{n}^{d} italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚Äúgoverned by g ùëî g italic_g ‚Äù or ‚Äúaccording to g ùëî g italic_g ‚Äù. The factor 1 / 2 1 2 1/2 1 / 2 in the acceptance probability is there in order to make the algorithm lazy , i.e.¬†it can be described as, for each time step, flipping a fair coin to decide to either move according to a given Markov transition matrix or to stay put. Lazy chains are convenient to work with, as they never exhibit periodicity behavior. In particular the transition matrix of a lazy reversible Markov chain has only nonnegative eigenvalues. The natural discretization of a continuous time Markov chain is always a lazy discrete time chain and results for the continuous time chain typically carry over.

In this paper, the function g = g n ùëî subscript ùëî ùëõ g=g_{n} italic_g = italic_g start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT will be of the form g ( x ) = f ( x ) m n ùëî ùë• ùëì superscript ùë• subscript ùëö ùëõ g(x)=f(x)^{m_{n}} italic_g ( italic_x ) = italic_f ( italic_x ) start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , m n ‚Üí ‚àû ‚Üí subscript ùëö ùëõ m_{n}\rightarrow\infty italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚Üí ‚àû , where f ùëì f italic_f has continuous partial derivatives up to order 3 and a unique global maximum in the interior of [ 0 , 1 ] d superscript 0 1 ùëë [0,1]^{d} [ 0 , 1 ] start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT . For simplicity we take m n = n subscript ùëö ùëõ ùëõ m_{n}=n italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_n as the generalization will be obvious. We further assume that f ùëì f italic_f has at most finitely many stationary points and that the Hessian is negative definite at the global maximum. (Many of these conditions can be relaxed; this will be pointed out later.) As a stepping stone and of independent interest, attention will also be paid to weighted random walks on graphs where asymptotically all the mass of the stationary distribution is concentrated to a single vertex.

The problem with mixing appears when there are other local maxima than the global maximum. It is easy to see that in such a case, starting from a state corresponding to a local but not global maximum, there is a vanishing probability that the MCMC will leave that mode within less than a time which is exponential in n ùëõ n italic_n .

In such situations a common method to overcome is to use simulated annealing (SA). Originally SA was designed to find a global optimum (of g ùëî g italic_g in this case), but in the MCMC situation we just modify it so that we stop at a nonzero temperature. The idea is to replace the original MCMC with a time inhomogeneous Markov chain, where at time t ùë° t italic_t , the state of the chain is updated according to g n , t = f Œ∑ t ( n ) subscript ùëî ùëõ ùë° superscript ùëì subscript ùúÇ ùë° ùëõ g_{n,t}=f^{\eta_{t}(n)} italic_g start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n , italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_f start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_Œ∑ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_n ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , where Œ∑ 1 ( n ) , Œ∑ 2 ( n ) , ‚Ä¶ subscript ùúÇ 1 ùëõ subscript ùúÇ 2 ùëõ ‚Ä¶ \eta_{1}(n),\eta_{2}(n),\ldots italic_Œ∑ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_n ) , italic_Œ∑ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_n ) , ‚Ä¶ are hopefully chosen so that convergence is sped up considerably. Typically the Œ∑ t = Œ∑ t ( n ) subscript ùúÇ ùë° subscript ùúÇ ùë° ùëõ \eta_{t}=\eta_{t}(n) italic_Œ∑ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_Œ∑ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_n ) :s are much smaller than n ùëõ n italic_n for a long time, but will be raised to n ùëõ n italic_n at the end of the process. According to standard language, we sometimes refer to the Œ∑ t subscript ùúÇ ùë° \eta_{t} italic_Œ∑ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT :s as inverse temperatures. SA is usually heuristic and few formal studies have been made. Woodard et.¬†al. [ 18 ] makes a valuable general analysis, but produce results that for the given situation are neither as strong nor as concrete as the ones presented here. There have also been a handful of studies of the closely related simulated tempering algorithm, see [ 2 ] , [ 8 ] , [ 15 ] , where the idea is to move back and forth between different temperatures. Results there are partly applicable to our situation and show that mixing in polynomial time can be possible, albeit of fairly high power.

Remarks.

  • (i)

    Many of the assumptions on f ùëì f italic_f can be relaxed. For example, f ùëì f italic_f does not need to be differentiable at c ùëê c italic_c ; it may have a peak there instead. Another possible change is to let the global maximum be on the boundary of B n d superscript subscript ùêµ ùëõ ùëë B_{n}^{d} italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT . The analysis needs only minor modifications and in fact, convergence for a unimodal f ùëì f italic_f of these kinds is even faster and the analysis may be considerably simpler.

    A third, and obvious, generalization is to restrict f ùëì f italic_f to a subspace S ùëÜ S italic_S of B d n superscript subscript ùêµ ùëë ùëõ B_{d}^{n} italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT under some assumptions on S ùëÜ S italic_S , e.g.¬†that S ùëÜ S italic_S be path-connected and S 0 ¬Ø = S ¬Ø superscript ùëÜ 0 ùëÜ \overline{S^{0}}=S over¬Ø start_ARG italic_S start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_ARG = italic_S .

    A fourth and also obvious observation is that the governing function f n superscript ùëì ùëõ f^{n} italic_f start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT may be replaced with f m n superscript ùëì subscript ùëö ùëõ f^{m_{n}} italic_f start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT for any m n ‚Üí ‚àû ‚Üí subscript ùëö ùëõ m_{n}\rightarrow\infty italic_m start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ‚Üí ‚àû , as we claimed at the outset.

  • (ii)

  • (iii)

    As for the simpler situation, one will typically not know the difference between f ( c ) ùëì ùëê f(c) italic_f ( italic_c ) and f ( a ) ùëì ùëé f(a) italic_f ( italic_a ) for a second largest local maximum a ùëé a italic_a .   • (iv)

    It is not necessary that the global maximum is unique.     In a case like this, we may have that f ùëì f italic_f has no other local maxima than the multiple global maxima.   • (v)

    The essential ideas of our procedure is to first find K ùêæ K italic_K sufficiently large for œÄ K superscript ùúã ùêæ \pi^{K} italic_œÄ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_K end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT to become sufficiently close to œÄ n superscript ùúã ùëõ \pi^{n} italic_œÄ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , then run a first stage according to f K superscript ùëì ùêæ f^{K} italic_f start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_K end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT to achieve mixing and then finally a second stage of O ( n log ‚Å° n ) ùëÇ ùëõ ùëõ O(n\log n) italic_O ( italic_n roman_log italic_n ) steps according to f n superscript ùëì ùëõ f^{n} italic_f start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT .   • (vii)

    Another trick that may be useful in practice is to observe that since to mix in our situation is essentially to find (a unimodal neighborhood of) the global maximum and perform a weighted random walk from there for a short time. Hence it will not matter if we instead of using g ùëî g italic_g , use max ‚Å° ( g , M ) ùëî ùëÄ \max(g,M) roman_max ( italic_g , italic_M ) where the constant M ùëÄ M italic_M is chosen sufficiently small that the peak where the global maximum is located does not become ‚Äútoo thin‚Äù to be easily found for simple random walk. To find a suitable M ùëÄ M italic_M , we may collect a uniform sample of points in the domain of g ùëî g italic_g , compute g ùëî g italic_g there and then take M ùëÄ M italic_M to be the N ùëÅ N italic_N ‚Äôth largest observation, where N ùëÅ N italic_N depends on how much risk of making the peak of the global maximum too thin that we are prepared to take. Using this trick may be essential if the graph of g ùëî g italic_g contains moat like structures that effectively disconnect the domain.

Example. Latent Dirichlet Allocation. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is a model used to latent topics in documents. It was introduced in Blei et.¬†al. [ 3 ] and has reached an almost iconic status in the family of probabilistic models for textual data and many variants have been developed since.

A large corpus of documents is to be classified into topics and we want to determine for each word in each document which topic it comes from. Knowing this we can also classify the documents according to the proportion of words of the different topics it contains. LDA is a generative Bayesian model and the setup is that one has a fixed number D ùê∑ D italic_D of documents of lengths N d subscript ùëÅ ùëë N_{d} italic_N start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUBSCRIPT a fixed set of topics t 1 , t 2 , ‚Ä¶ , t K subscript ùë° 1 subscript ùë° 2 ‚Ä¶ subscript ùë° ùêæ t_{1},t_{2},\ldots,t_{K} italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚Ä¶ , italic_t start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_K end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and a vocabulary that consists of a fixed set of word types (i.e.¬†distinct words that appear somewhere in the corpus) w 1 , w 2 , ‚Ä¶ , w V subscript ùë§ 1 subscript ùë§ 2 ‚Ä¶ subscript ùë§ ùëâ w_{1},w_{2},\ldots,w_{V} italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , ‚Ä¶ , italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_V end_POSTSUBSCRIPT . These are specified in advance. The number of topics is usually not large, whereas the number of words in the vocabulary is. The first example was the situation described above, i.e.¬†the corpus consisted of three documents of length n i . subscript ùëõ ùëñ n_{i.} italic_n start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i . end_POSTSUBSCRIPT each, consisting of 9 / 10 9 10 9/10 9 / 10 of word 1 and 1 / 10 1 10 1/10 1 / 10 of word 2 in the first document and then two documents consisting of all 2 2 2 2 :s and all 3 3 3 3 :s respectively. The hyperparameters were Œ± = Œ≤ = 1 ùõº ùõΩ 1 \alpha=\beta=1 italic_Œ± = italic_Œ≤ = 1 . We will refer to this corpus as the toy corpus.

We first checked the behavior of standard collapsed Gibbs sampling without SA, started from a state uniformly chosen over the 2 n superscript 2 ùëõ 2^{n} 2 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT topic assignments (where n = n . . n=n_{..} italic_n = italic_n start_POSTSUBSCRIPT . . end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ), to see how often it ended up in each of the three modes. The experiment was run 1000 1000 1000 1000 times with n . . = 1200 n_{..}=1200 italic_n start_POSTSUBSCRIPT . . end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 1200 . Figure 5 shows a histogram over three modes where these are characterized by their respective log posterior density. We find that the problem of multimodality is real and that the mode that we most frequently end up in is in fact the worst one.

For SA, we made 500 500 500 500 runs each for Œ∫ = 1 , 2 , 4 , 8 , 16 , 32 , 64 , 128 ùúÖ 1 2 4 8 16 32 64 128 \kappa=1,2,4,8,16,32,64,128 italic_Œ∫ = 1 , 2 , 4 , 8 , 16 , 32 , 64 , 128 for 5 n 2 5 superscript ùëõ 2 5n^{2} 5 italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT time steps. Each run was finished with Œ∫ = n ùúÖ ùëõ \kappa=n italic_Œ∫ = italic_n for n 2 superscript ùëõ 2 n^{2} italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT steps. Each run was started in the second best mode of f ùëì f italic_f . Figure 6 shows, for each Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ , a histogram over what modes the annealed collapsed Gibbs ended in. Note that for Œ∫ ‚â§ 4 ùúÖ 4 \kappa\leq 4 italic_Œ∫ ‚â§ 4 , the fitness landscape has been made too flat and the results are indistinguishable from standard Gibbs with uniform start. For Œ∫ ‚â• 32 ùúÖ 32 \kappa\geq 32 italic_Œ∫ ‚â• 32 , the opposite happens and the sampler is stuck in the starting mode. For Œ∫ = 8 , 16 ùúÖ 8 16 \kappa=8,16 italic_Œ∫ = 8 , 16 , the desired behavior occurs and the sampler finds the optimal mode virtually all the time.

We further studied the behavior on real data; we created small corpora made up of three different translations (English, Swedish and French) of the novel Three men and a boat by Jerome K. Jerome. We set up the corpus by first removing common stopwords from each language (such as a, the, etc. ). Then, we extracted the first words of each chapter until we fulfilled two criteria; first that each word should occur ten or more times and second that the total number of tokens should be so that 80% of the words were in English and 10% in Swedish and French, respectively. In total, the corpus was made up of 4999 word tokens (3963 English, 531 French, and 505 Swedish word tokens).

Using these words, we created three corpora with different document definitions.

  1. 1.

    Corpus 1: We combined Ch. 1-10 and 11-19 per language. Hence we have got document: two English, two French, and two Swedish.

  2. 2.

    Corpus 2: As in Corpus 1, but the English tokens were instead split up into documents that each covered two chapters. Hence, this corpus had fourteen documents: ten English, two French, and two Swedish.

  3. 3.

    Corpus 3: As in Corpus 1, but the English tokens were divided into five documents covering four chapters each. Hence, this corpus had nine documents: five English, two French, and two Swedish.

These experiments were run with K = 3 ùêæ 3 K=3 italic_K = 3 and 100 runs for each value of Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ . The hyperparameter values were again Œ± = Œ≤ = 1 ùõº ùõΩ 1 \alpha=\beta=1 italic_Œ± = italic_Œ≤ = 1 . In each case, the best mode in terms of posterior probability was to classify all English documents as one topic, all French documents as another topic and all Swedish documents as a third topic. There were other modes however, and our runs were started in the second best mode, which was to consider the French and Swedish documents together as one topic and the third topic empty.

In Figure 7 , we find the results on Corpus 1. One can read out that there is a range of Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ values around 128 128 128 128 , where almost all runs end up in the best mode. For smaller Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ , the behavior is like standard Gibbs sampling started from a uniformly random configuration and for larger Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ we get stuck in the starting mode.

The results on Corpus 2 are found in Figure 8 . One can read out that some small and bordering on significant improvement over standard Gibbs started from uniformity was achieved for Œ∫ = 32 , 64 ùúÖ 32 64 \kappa=32,64 italic_Œ∫ = 32 , 64 . In order to check if this improvement was a random phenomenon, we performed a refined search for higher values of Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ without finding further improvement.

In Figure 9 , the results for Corpus 3 are found. Here a clear and significant improvement is found for Œ∫ ùúÖ \kappa italic_Œ∫ between 150 and 180. This result is not as pronounced as for Corpus 1 but a lot more than for Corpus 2, which was intuitively anticipated, since Corpus 3 is ‚Äùin between‚Äù Corpus 1 and Corpus 2.

It is not clear to us why dividing the English text into a larger number of documents seems to harm the performance of SA and it would be interesting to understand that, something we leave for future work.

‚ñ° ‚ñ° \Box ‚ñ°

Example. 3S1 phase shifts from an analysis of neutron-proton scattering cross sections. I am grateful to Christian Forss√©n and Andreas Ekstr√∂m who provided the data in this example.

Bayesian analysis methods are increasingly being used in theoretical nuclear physics [ 17 ] . A specific example is the determination of parameters in a chiral effective field theory description of the low-energy, strong interaction between neutrons and protons (see e.g. [ 4 ] , [ 9 ] , [ 13 ] , and references therein). In short, we seek to find the parameter vector Œ∏ ùúÉ \theta italic_Œ∏ that minimizes the deviation between the model and experimental data. In this specific case, the calibration data corresponds to the 3S1 phase shifts from an analysis of neutron-proton scattering cross sections [ 16 ] ). See, e.g. [ 17 ] for more details on the definition of the likelihood function.

In this example a Bayesian model of the standard form with two parameters,
